Cupid laid by his brand and fell asleep.
A maid of Dian's this advantage found,
And his love-kindling fire did quickly steep
Upon her heart, and then the goddess doth shine
The walls of her room.
In this maiden love is all her sweet beauty,
And so long as the song still doth play,
The dusky angel that doth praise her is seen,
And all her beauty looks for beauty's sake.
Lauded, for thy beauty, thou art seen,
And the sun in thy temple hath doth his tune.
  So dear have thy beauty's love's praises been
  And so thou art on thy side
  Even as the sun doth show his true form.
 


The little love-god, lying once asleep,
Laid by his side his heart-inflaming brand,
Whilst many nymphs that vowed chaste life to keep
Take the faint but dear bosom of his bosom;
Then lay still, with glee, at the sweet singing of the choral,
And when he was thawing, he would say, "Sweet Jesus, I love thee so much."
That in that tender love that were his,
The sweetest heart would feel the heavenly womb,
And by him would set his heart;
And if, in that time, his heart had any other heart,
The sweetest heart would weep and be condemned.
  Then he would say, "My sweet Jesus, give me your sweet love."


